-function variants were generally selected against, we also find specific clinical conditions linked to gain-of-function mutations. For example, we detect an association between gain-of-function mutations in the 3&#39;-end and autism spectrum disorder. To experimentally validate APARENT2&#39;s predictions, we assayed clinically relevant variants in multiple cell lines, including microglia-derived cells.A sequence-to-function model based on deep residual learning enables accurate functional interpretation of genetic variants in polyadenylation signals and, when coupled with large human variation databases, elucidates the link between functional 3&#39;-end mutations and human health.&#34;},{&#34;apaCitation&#34;:&#34;Nair, S., Barrett, A., Li, D., Raney, B. J., Lee, B. T., Kerpedjiev, P., … Kundaje, A. (2022). The dynseq browser track shows context-specific features at nucleotide resolution. &lt;i>Nature Genetics&lt;/i>.&#34;,&#34;capCitation&#34;:&#34;&lt;span class=\&#34;title\&#34;>\n  &lt;span>The dynseq browser track shows context-specific features at nucleotide resolution.&lt;/span>\n  &lt;i>Nature genetics&lt;/i>\n&lt;/span>\n&lt;span class=\&#34;authors\&#34;>Nair, S., Barrett, A., Li, D., Raney, B. J., Lee, B. T., Kerpedjiev, P., Ramalingam, V., Pampari, A., Lekschas, F., Wang, T., Haeussler, M., Kundaje, A.&lt;/span>\n\n&lt;span class=\&#34;details\&#34;>\n   &lt;span class=\&#34;year\&#34;>2022&lt;/span>\n&lt;/span>&#34;,&#34;chicagoCitation&#34;:&#34;Nair, Surag, Arjun Barrett, Daofeng Li, Brian J. Raney, Brian T. Lee, et al. 2022. “The Dynseq Browser Track Shows Context-Specific Features at Nucleotide Resolution.” &lt;i>Nature Genetics&lt;/i>.&#34;,&#34;detail&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;&lt;p class=\&#34;doi\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://doi.org/10.1038/s41588-022-01194-w\&#34;>DOI 10.1038/s41588-022-01194-w&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;pub-med\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/36241719\&#34;>PubMedID 36241719&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;DOI: 10.1038/s41588-022-01194-w, https://doi.org/10.1038/s41588-022-01194-w\n\nPubMedID: 36241719, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/36241719&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:null},&#34;doiId&#34;:&#34;10.1038/s41588-022-01194-w&#34;,&#34;doiUrl&#34;:&#34;https://doi.org/10.1038/s41588-022-01194-w&#34;,&#34;featured&#34;:false,&#34;firstPublished&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;Oct 14, 2022 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Oct 14, 2022 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:&#34;2022-10-14T00:00:00.000-07:00&#34;},&#34;mlaCitation&#34;:&#34;Nair, Surag et al. “The Dynseq Browser Track Shows Context-Specific Features at Nucleotide Resolution.” &lt;i>Nature genetics&lt;/i> (2022): n. pag. Print.&#34;,&#34;pubMedId&#34;:&#34;36241719&#34;,&#34;pubMedUrl&#34;:&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/36241719&#34;,&#34;publicationId&#34;:&#34;859633&#34;,&#34;title&#34;:&#34;The dynseq browser track shows context-specific features at nucleotide resolution.&#34;,&#34;type&#34;:&#34;article&#34;,&#34;contentClass&#34;:&#34;publication article&#34;,&#34;abstract&#34;:null},{&#34;apaCitation&#34;:&#34;Wang, S. K., Nair, S., Li, R., Kraft, K., Pampari, A., Patel, A., … Chang, H. Y. (2022). Single-cell multiome of the human retina and deep learning nominate causal variants in complex eye diseases. &lt;i>Cell Genomics&lt;/i>, &lt;i>2&lt;/i>(8).&#34;,&#34;capCitation&#34;:&#34;&lt;span class=\&#34;title\&#34;>\n  &lt;span>Single-cell multiome of the human retina and deep learning nominate causal variants in complex eye diseases.&lt;/span>\n  &lt;i>Cell genomics&lt;/i>\n&lt;/span>\n&lt;span class=\&#34;authors\&#34;>Wang, S. K., Nair, S., Li, R., Kraft, K., Pampari, A., Patel, A., Kang, J. B., Luong, C., Kundaje, A., Chang, H. Y.&lt;/span>\n\n&lt;span class=\&#34;details\&#34;>\n   &lt;span class=\&#34;year\&#34;>2022&lt;/span>; &lt;span class=\&#34;volume\&#34;>2 (8)&lt;/span>\n&lt;/span>&#34;,&#34;chicagoCitation&#34;:&#34;Wang, Sean K., Surag Nair, Rui Li, Katerina Kraft, Anusri Pampari, et al. 2022. “Single-Cell Multiome of the Human Retina and Deep Learning Nominate Causal Variants in Complex Eye Diseases.” &lt;i>Cell Genomics&lt;/i> 2 (8).&#34;,&#34;detail&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;&lt;h4>Abstract&lt;/h4>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;abstract\&#34;>Genome-wide association studies (GWASs) of eye disorders have identified hundreds of genetic variants associated with ocular disease. However, the vast majority of these variants are noncoding, making it challenging to interpret their function. Here we present a joint single-cell atlas of gene expression and chromatin accessibility of the adult human retina with more than 50,000 cells, which we used to analyze single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) implicated by GWASs of age-related macular degeneration, glaucoma, diabetic retinopathy, myopia, and type 2 macular telangiectasia. We integrate this atlas with a HiChIP enhancer connectome, expression quantitative trait loci (eQTL) data, and base-resolution deep learning models to predict noncoding SNPs with causal roles in eye disease, assess SNP impact on transcription factor binding, and define their known and novel target genes. Our efforts nominate pathogenic SNP-target gene interactions for multiple vision disorders and provide a potentially powerful resource for interpreting noncoding variation in the eye.&lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;doi\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://doi.org/10.1016/j.xgen.2022.100164\&#34;>DOI 10.1016/j.xgen.2022.100164&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;pub-med\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/36277849\&#34;>PubMedID 36277849&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Abstract:\nGenome-wide association studies (GWASs) of eye disorders have identified hundreds of genetic variants associated with ocular disease. However, the vast majority of these variants are noncoding, making it challenging to interpret their function. Here we present a joint single-cell atlas of gene expression and chromatin accessibility of the adult human retina with more than 50,000 cells, which we used to analyze single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) implicated by GWASs of age-related macular degeneration, glaucoma, diabetic retinopathy, myopia, and type 2 macular telangiectasia. We integrate this atlas with a HiChIP enhancer connectome, expression quantitative trait loci (eQTL) data, and base-resolution deep learning models to predict noncoding SNPs with causal roles in eye disease, assess SNP impact on transcription factor binding, and define their known and novel target genes. Our efforts nominate pathogenic SNP-target gene interactions for multiple vision disorders and provide a potentially powerful resource for interpreting noncoding variation in the eye.\nDOI: 10.1016/j.xgen.2022.100164, https://doi.org/10.1016/j.xgen.2022.100164\n\nPubMedID: 36277849, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/36277849&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:null},&#34;doiId&#34;:&#34;10.1016/j.xgen.2022.100164&#34;,&#34;doiUrl&#34;:&#34;https://doi.org/10.1016/j.xgen.2022.100164&#34;,&#34;featured&#34;:false,&#34;firstPublished&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;Aug 10, 2022 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Aug 10, 2022 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:&#34;2022-08-10T00:00:00.000-07:00&#34;},&#34;mlaCitation&#34;:&#34;Wang, Sean K. et al. “Single-Cell Multiome of the Human Retina and Deep Learning Nominate Causal Variants in Complex Eye Diseases.” &lt;i>Cell genomics&lt;/i> 2.8 (2022): n. pag. Print.&#34;,&#34;pubMedId&#34;:&#34;36277849&#34;,&#34;pubMedUrl&#34;:&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/36277849&#34;,&#34;publicationId&#34;:&#34;860352&#34;,&#34;title&#34;:&#34;Single-cell multiome of the human retina and deep learning nominate causal variants in complex eye diseases.&#34;,&#34;type&#34;:&#34;article&#34;,&#34;contentClass&#34;:&#34;publication article&#34;,&#34;abstract&#34;:&#34;Genome-wide association studies (GWASs) of eye disorders have identified hundreds of genetic variants associated with ocular disease. However, the vast majority of these variants are noncoding, making it challenging to interpret their function. Here we present a joint single-cell atlas of gene expression and chromatin accessibility of the adult human retina with more than 50,000 cells, which we used to analyze single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) implicated by GWASs of age-related macular degeneration, glaucoma, diabetic retinopathy, myopia, and type 2 macular telangiectasia. We integrate this atlas with a HiChIP enhancer connectome, expression quantitative trait loci (eQTL) data, and base-resolution deep learning models to predict noncoding SNPs with causal roles in eye disease, assess SNP impact on transcription factor binding, and define their known and novel target genes. Our efforts nominate pathogenic SNP-target gene interactions for multiple vision disorders and provide a potentially powerful resource for interpreting noncoding variation in the eye.&#34;},{&#34;apaCitation&#34;:&#34;Kundaje, A., &amp;amp; Meuleman, W. (2022). Automated sequence-based annotation and interpretation of the human genome. &lt;i>Nature Genetics&lt;/i>.&#34;,&#34;capCitation&#34;:&#34;&lt;span class=\&#34;title\&#34;>\n  &lt;span>Automated sequence-based annotation and interpretation of the human genome.&lt;/span>\n  &lt;i>Nature genetics&lt;/i>\n&lt;/span>\n&lt;span class=\&#34;authors\&#34;>Kundaje, A., Meuleman, W.&lt;/span>\n\n&lt;span class=\&#34;details\&#34;>\n   &lt;span class=\&#34;year\&#34;>2022&lt;/span>\n&lt;/span>&#34;,&#34;chicagoCitation&#34;:&#34;Kundaje, Anshul, and Wouter Meuleman. 2022. “Automated Sequence-Based Annotation and Interpretation of the Human Genome.” &lt;i>Nature Genetics&lt;/i>.&#34;,&#34;detail&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;&lt;p class=\&#34;doi\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#