A., Balsubramani, A., Hardison, R. C., Kundaje, A., Mahony, S.&lt;/span>\n\n&lt;span class=\&#34;details\&#34;>\n   &lt;span class=\&#34;year\&#34;>1800&lt;/span>\n&lt;/span>&#34;,&#34;chicagoCitation&#34;:&#34;Cochran, Kelly, Divyanshi Srivastava, Avanti Shrikumar, Akshay Balsubramani, Ross C. Hardison, et al. 1800. “Domain Adaptive Neural Networks Improve Cross-Species Prediction of Transcription Factor Binding.” &lt;i>Genome Research&lt;/i>.&#34;,&#34;detail&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;&lt;h4>Abstract&lt;/h4>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;abstract\&#34;>The intrinsic DNA sequence preferences and cell-type specific cooperative partners of transcription factors (TFs) are typically highly conserved. Hence, despite the rapid evolutionary turnover of individual TF binding sites, predictive sequence models of cell-type specific genomic occupancy of a TF in one species should generalize to closely matched cell types in a related species. To assess the viability of cross-species TF binding prediction, we train neural networks to discriminate ChIP-seq peak locations from genomic background and evaluate their performance within and across species. Cross-species predictive performance is consistently worse than within-species performance, which we show is caused in part by species-specific repeats. To account for this domain shift, we use an augmented network architecture to automatically discourage learning of training species-specific sequence features. This domain adaptation approach corrects for prediction errors on species-specific repeats and improves overall cross-species model performance. Our results demonstrate that cross-species TF binding prediction is feasible when models account for domain shifts driven by species-specific repeats.&lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;doi\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://doi.org/10.1101/gr.275394.121\&#34;>DOI 10.1101/gr.275394.121&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;pub-med\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/35042722\&#34;>PubMedID 35042722&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Abstract:\nThe intrinsic DNA sequence preferences and cell-type specific cooperative partners of transcription factors (TFs) are typically highly conserved. Hence, despite the rapid evolutionary turnover of individual TF binding sites, predictive sequence models of cell-type specific genomic occupancy of a TF in one species should generalize to closely matched cell types in a related species. To assess the viability of cross-species TF binding prediction, we train neural networks to discriminate ChIP-seq peak locations from genomic background and evaluate their performance within and across species. Cross-species predictive performance is consistently worse than within-species performance, which we show is caused in part by species-specific repeats. To account for this domain shift, we use an augmented network architecture to automatically discourage learning of training species-specific sequence features. This domain adaptation approach corrects for prediction errors on species-specific repeats and improves overall cross-species model performance. Our results demonstrate that cross-species TF binding prediction is feasible when models account for domain shifts driven by species-specific repeats.\nDOI: 10.1101/gr.275394.121, https://doi.org/10.1101/gr.275394.121\n\nPubMedID: 35042722, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/35042722&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:null},&#34;doiId&#34;:&#34;10.1101/gr.275394.121&#34;,&#34;doiUrl&#34;:&#34;https://doi.org/10.1101/gr.275394.121&#34;,&#34;featured&#34;:false,&#34;firstPublished&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;Jan 18, 2022 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Jan 18, 2022 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:&#34;2022-01-18T00:00:00.000-08:00&#34;},&#34;mlaCitation&#34;:&#34;Cochran, Kelly et al. “Domain Adaptive Neural Networks Improve Cross-Species Prediction of Transcription Factor Binding.” &lt;i>Genome research&lt;/i> (1800): n. pag. Print.&#34;,&#34;pubMedId&#34;:&#34;35042722&#34;,&#34;pubMedUrl&#34;:&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/35042722&#34;,&#34;publicationId&#34;:&#34;837716&#34;,&#34;title&#34;:&#34;Domain adaptive neural networks improve cross-species prediction of transcription factor binding.&#34;,&#34;type&#34;:&#34;article&#34;,&#34;contentClass&#34;:&#34;publication article&#34;,&#34;abstract&#34;:&#34;The intrinsic DNA sequence preferences and cell-type specific cooperative partners of transcription factors (TFs) are typically highly conserved. Hence, despite the rapid evolutionary turnover of individual TF binding sites, predictive sequence models of cell-type specific genomic occupancy of a TF in one species should generalize to closely matched cell types in a related species. To assess the viability of cross-species TF binding prediction, we train neural networks to discriminate ChIP-seq peak locations from genomic background and evaluate their performance within and across species. Cross-species predictive performance is consistently worse than within-species performance, which we show is caused in part by species-specific repeats. To account for this domain shift, we use an augmented network architecture to automatically discourage learning of training species-specific sequence features. This domain adaptation approach corrects for prediction errors on species-specific repeats and improves overall cross-species model performance. Our results demonstrate that cross-species TF binding prediction is feasible when models account for domain shifts driven by species-specific repeats.&#34;},{&#34;apaCitation&#34;:&#34;Cheng, P., Wirka, R. C., Clarke, L. S., Zhao, Q., Kundu, R., Nguyen, T., … Quertermous, T. (2022). ZEB2 Shapes the Epigenetic Landscape of Atherosclerosis. &lt;i>Circulation&lt;/i>, &lt;i>145&lt;/i>(6).&#34;,&#34;capCitation&#34;:&#34;&lt;span class=\&#34;title\&#34;>\n  &lt;span>ZEB2 Shapes the Epigenetic Landscape of Atherosclerosis&lt;/span>\n  &lt;i>Circulation&lt;/i>\n&lt;/span>\n&lt;span class=\&#34;authors\&#34;>Cheng, P., Wirka, R. C., Clarke, L., Zhao, Q., Kundu, R., Nguyen, T., Nair, S., Sharma, D., Kim, H., Shi, H., Assimes, T., Kim, J., Kundaje, A., Quertermous, T.&lt;/span>\n\n&lt;span class=\&#34;details\&#34;>\n   &lt;span class=\&#34;year\&#34;>2022&lt;/span>; &lt;span class=\&#34;volume\&#34;>145 (6)&lt;/span>&lt;span class=\&#34;pages\&#34;>: 469–485&lt;/span>\n&lt;/span>&#34;,&#34;chicagoCitation&#34;:&#34;Cheng, Paul, Robert C. Wirka, Lee Shoa Clarke, Quanyi Zhao, Ramendra Kundu, et al. 2022. “ZEB2 Shapes the Epigenetic Landscape of Atherosclerosis.” &lt;i>Circulation&lt;/i> 145 (6). American Heart Association.&#34;,&#34;detail&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;&lt;h4>Abstract&lt;/h4>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;abstract\&#34;>Background: Smooth muscle cells (SMC) transition into a number of different phenotypes during atherosclerosis, including those that resemble fibroblasts and chondrocytes, and make up the majority of cells in the atherosclerotic plaque. To better understand the epigenetic and transcriptional mechanisms that mediate these cell state changes, and how they relate to risk for coronary artery disease (CAD), we have investigated the causality and function of transcription factors (TFs) at genome wide associated loci. Methods: We employed CRISPR-Cas 9 genome and epigenome editing to identify the causal gene and cell(s) for a complex CAD GWAS signal at 2q22.3. Subsequently, single-cell epigenetic and transcriptomic profiling in murine models and human coronary artery smooth muscle cells were employed to understand the cellular and molecular mechanism by which this CAD risk gene exerts its function. Results: CRISPR-Cas 9 genome and epigenome editing showed that the complex CAD genetic signals within a genomic region at 2q22.3 lie within smooth muscle long-distance enhancers for ZEB2, a TF extensively studied in the context of epithelial mesenchymal transition (EMT) in development and cancer. ZEB2 regulates SMC phenotypic transition through chromatin remodeling that obviates accessibility and disrupts both Notch and TGFβ signaling, thus altering the epigenetic trajectory of SMC transitions. SMC specific loss of ZEB2 resulted in an inability of transitioning SMCs to turn off contractile programing and take on a fibroblast-like phenotype, but accelerated the formation of chondromyocytes, mirroring features of high-risk atherosclerotic plaques in human coronary arteries. Conclusions: These studies identify ZEB2 as a new CAD GWAS gene that affects features of plaque vulnerability through direct effects on the epigenome, providing a new thereapeutic approach to target vascular disease.&lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;doi\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;http://dx.doi.org/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.121.057789\&#34;>DOI 10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.121.057789&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Abstract:\nBackground: Smooth muscle cells (SMC) transition into a number of different phenotypes during atherosclerosis, including those that resemble fibroblasts and chondrocytes, and make up the majority of cells in the atherosclerotic plaque. To better understand the epigenetic and transcriptional mechanisms that mediate these cell state changes, and how they relate to risk for coronary artery disease (CAD), we have investigated the causality and function of transcription factors (TFs) at genome wide associated loci. Methods: We employed CRISPR-Cas 9 genome and epigenome editing to identify the causal gene and cell(s) for a complex CAD GWAS signal at 2q22.3. Subsequently, single-cell epigenetic and transcriptomic profiling in murine models and human coronary artery smooth muscle cells were employed to understand the cellular and molecular mechanism by which this CAD risk gene exerts its function. Results: CRISPR-Cas 9 genome and epigenome editing showed that the complex CAD genetic signals within a genomic region at 2q22.3 lie within smooth muscle long-distance enhancers for ZEB2, a TF extensively studied in the context of epithelial mesenchymal transition (EMT) in development and cancer. ZEB2 regulates SMC phenotypic transition through chromatin remodeling that obviates accessibility and disrupts both Notch and TGFβ signaling, thus altering the epigenetic trajectory of SMC transitions. SMC specific loss of ZEB2 resulted in an inability of transitioning SMCs to turn off contractile programing and take on a fibroblast-like phenotype, but accelerated the formation of chondromyocytes, mirroring features of high-risk atherosclerotic plaques in human coronary arteries. Conclusions: These studies identify ZEB2 as a new CAD GWAS gene that affects features of plaque vulnerability through direct effects on the epigenome, providing a new thereapeutic approach to target vascular disease.\nDOI: 10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.121.057789, http://dx.doi.org/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.121.057789&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:null},&#34;doiId&#34;:&#34;10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.121.057789&#34;,&#34;doiUrl&#34;:&#34;http://dx.doi.org/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.121.057789&#34;,&#34;featured&#34;:false,&#34;firstPublished&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;Jan 6, 2022 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Jan 6, 2022 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:&#34;2022-01-06T00:00:00.000-08:00&#34;},&#34;mlaCitation&#34;:&#34;Cheng, Paul et al. “ZEB2 Shapes the Epigenetic Landscape of Atherosclerosis.” &lt;i>Circulation&lt;/i> 145.6 (2022): n. pag. Print.&#34;,&#34;pubMedId&#34;:null,&#34;pubMedUrl&#34;:null,&#34;publicationId&#34;:&#34;842417&#34;,&#34;title&#34;:&#34;ZEB2 Shapes the Epigenetic Landscape of Atherosclerosis&#34;,&#34;type&#34;:&#34;article&#34;,&#34;contentClass&#34;:&#34;publication article&#34;,&#34;abstract&#34;:&#34;Background: Smooth muscle cells (SMC) transition into a number of different phenotypes during atherosclerosis, including those that resemble fibroblasts and chondrocytes, and make up the majority of cells i