ion of breast cancer. &lt;i>CANCER RESEARCH&lt;/i>. AMER ASSOC CANCER RESEARCH.&#34;,&#34;capCitation&#34;:&#34;&lt;span class=\&#34;title\&#34;>\n  &lt;span>Cell-free DNA fragments inform epigenomic mechanisms for early detection of breast cancer.&lt;/span>\n  \n&lt;/span>\n&lt;span class=\&#34;authors\&#34;>Gafni, E., Harvey, A., Jaroszewicz, A., Solari, O., Landolin, J., Barbirou, M., Miller, A., Tonellato, P. J., Kundaje, A., Jeffrey, S. S., Curtis, C., Sledge, G. W., Giresi, P., Boley, N.&lt;/span>\n\n&lt;span class=\&#34;details\&#34;>\n  &lt;span class=\&#34;publisher\&#34;>AMER ASSOC CANCER RESEARCH.&lt;/span> &lt;span class=\&#34;year\&#34;>2021&lt;/span>\n&lt;/span>&#34;,&#34;chicagoCitation&#34;:&#34;Gafni, Erik, Adam Harvey, Artur Jaroszewicz, Omid Shams Solari, Jane Landolin, et al. 2021. “Cell-Free DNA Fragments Inform Epigenomic Mechanisms for Early Detection of Breast Cancer.” &lt;i>CANCER RESEARCH&lt;/i>. AMER ASSOC CANCER RESEARCH.&#34;,&#34;detail&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;&lt;p class=\&#34;wos\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://ws.isiknowledge.com/cps/openurl/service?url_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;amp;rft_id=info:ut/000680263504022\&#34;>Web of Science ID 000680263504022&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Web of Science ID: 000680263504022, https://ws.isiknowledge.com/cps/openurl/service?url_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_id=info:ut/000680263504022&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:null},&#34;doiId&#34;:null,&#34;doiUrl&#34;:null,&#34;featured&#34;:false,&#34;firstPublished&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;Jul 1, 2021 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Jul 1, 2021 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:&#34;2021-07-01T00:00:00.000-07:00&#34;},&#34;mlaCitation&#34;:&#34;Gafni, Erik et al. “Cell-Free DNA Fragments Inform Epigenomic Mechanisms for Early Detection of Breast Cancer.” &lt;i>CANCER RESEARCH&lt;/i> 2021: n. pag. Print.&#34;,&#34;pubMedId&#34;:null,&#34;pubMedUrl&#34;:null,&#34;publicationId&#34;:&#34;893446&#34;,&#34;title&#34;:&#34;Cell-free DNA fragments inform epigenomic mechanisms for early detection of breast cancer.&#34;,&#34;type&#34;:&#34;inproceedings&#34;,&#34;contentClass&#34;:&#34;publication inproceedings&#34;,&#34;abstract&#34;:null},{&#34;apaCitation&#34;:&#34;Markov, G. J., Mai, T., Nair, S., Shcherbina, A., Wang, Y. X., Burns, D. M., … Blau, H. M. (2021). AP-1 is a temporally regulated dual gatekeeper of reprogramming to pluripotency. &lt;i>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America&lt;/i>, &lt;i>118&lt;/i>(23).&#34;,&#34;capCitation&#34;:&#34;&lt;span class=\&#34;title\&#34;>\n  &lt;span>AP-1 is a temporally regulated dual gatekeeper of reprogramming to pluripotency.&lt;/span>\n  &lt;i>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America&lt;/i>\n&lt;/span>\n&lt;span class=\&#34;authors\&#34;>Markov, G. J., Mai, T., Nair, S., Shcherbina, A., Wang, Y. X., Burns, D. M., Kundaje, A., Blau, H. M.&lt;/span>\n\n&lt;span class=\&#34;details\&#34;>\n   &lt;span class=\&#34;year\&#34;>2021&lt;/span>; &lt;span class=\&#34;volume\&#34;>118 (23)&lt;/span>\n&lt;/span>&#34;,&#34;chicagoCitation&#34;:&#34;Markov, Glenn J., Thach Mai, Surag Nair, Anna Shcherbina, Yu Xin Wang, et al. 2021. “AP-1 Is a Temporally Regulated Dual Gatekeeper of Reprogramming to Pluripotency.” &lt;i>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America&lt;/i> 118 (23).&#34;,&#34;detail&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;&lt;h4>Abstract&lt;/h4>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;abstract\&#34;>Somatic cell transcription factors are critical to maintaining cellular identity and constitute a barrier to human somatic cell reprogramming; yet a comprehensive understanding of the mechanism of action is lacking. To gain insight, we examined epigenome remodeling at the onset of human nuclear reprogramming by profiling human fibroblasts after fusion with murine embryonic stem cells (ESCs). By assay for transposase-accessible chromatin with high-throughput sequencing (ATAC-seq) and chromatin immunoprecipitation sequencing we identified enrichment for the activator protein 1 (AP-1) transcription factor c-Jun at regions of early transient accessibility at fibroblast-specific enhancers. Expression of a dominant negative AP-1 mutant (dnAP-1) reduced accessibility and expression of fibroblast genes, overcoming the barrier to reprogramming. Remarkably, efficient reprogramming of human fibroblasts to induced pluripotent stem cells was achieved by transduction with vectors expressing SOX2, KLF4, and inducible dnAP-1, demonstrating that dnAP-1 can substitute for exogenous human OCT4. Mechanistically, we show that the AP-1 component c-Jun has two unexpected temporally distinct functions in human reprogramming: 1) to potentiate fibroblast enhancer accessibility and fibroblast-specific gene expression, and 2) to bind to and repress OCT4 as a complex with MBD3. Our findings highlight AP-1 as a previously unrecognized potent dual gatekeeper of the somatic cell state.&lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;doi\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.2104841118\&#34;>DOI 10.1073/pnas.2104841118&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;pub-med\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/34088849\&#34;>PubMedID 34088849&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Abstract:\nSomatic cell transcription factors are critical to maintaining cellular identity and constitute a barrier to human somatic cell reprogramming; yet a comprehensive understanding of the mechanism of action is lacking. To gain insight, we examined epigenome remodeling at the onset of human nuclear reprogramming by profiling human fibroblasts after fusion with murine embryonic stem cells (ESCs). By assay for transposase-accessible chromatin with high-throughput sequencing (ATAC-seq) and chromatin immunoprecipitation sequencing we identified enrichment for the activator protein 1 (AP-1) transcription factor c-Jun at regions of early transient accessibility at fibroblast-specific enhancers. Expression of a dominant negative AP-1 mutant (dnAP-1) reduced accessibility and expression of fibroblast genes, overcoming the barrier to reprogramming. Remarkably, efficient reprogramming of human fibroblasts to induced pluripotent stem cells was achieved by transduction with vectors expressing SOX2, KLF4, and inducible dnAP-1, demonstrating that dnAP-1 can substitute for exogenous human OCT4. Mechanistically, we show that the AP-1 component c-Jun has two unexpected temporally distinct functions in human reprogramming: 1) to potentiate fibroblast enhancer accessibility and fibroblast-specific gene expression, and 2) to bind to and repress OCT4 as a complex with MBD3. Our findings highlight AP-1 as a previously unrecognized potent dual gatekeeper of the somatic cell state.\nDOI: 10.1073/pnas.2104841118, https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.2104841118\n\nPubMedID: 34088849, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/34088849&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:null},&#34;doiId&#34;:&#34;10.1073/pnas.2104841118&#34;,&#34;doiUrl&#34;:&#34;https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.2104841118&#34;,&#34;featured&#34;:false,&#34;firstPublished&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;Jun 8, 2021 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Jun 8, 2021 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:&#34;2021-06-08T00:00:00.000-07:00&#34;},&#34;mlaCitation&#34;:&#34;Markov, Glenn J. et al. “AP-1 Is a Temporally Regulated Dual Gatekeeper of Reprogramming to Pluripotency.” &lt;i>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America&lt;/i> 118.23 (2021): n. pag. Print.&#34;,&#34;pubMedId&#34;:&#34;34088849&#34;,&#34;pubMedUrl&#34;:&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/34088849&#34;,&#34;publicationId&#34;:&#34;816943&#34;,&#34;title&#34;:&#34;AP-1 is a temporally regulated dual gatekeeper of reprogramming to pluripotency.&#34;,&#34;type&#34;:&#34;article&#34;,&#34;contentClass&#34;:&#34;publication article&#34;,&#34;abstract&#34;:&#34;Somatic cell transcription factors are critical to maintaining cellular identity and constitute a barrier to human somatic cell reprogramming; yet a comprehensive understanding of the mechanism of action is lacking. To gain insight, we examined epigenome remodeling at the onset of human nuclear reprogramming by profiling human fibroblasts after fusion with murine embryonic stem cells (ESCs). By assay for transposase-accessible chromatin with high-throughput sequencing (ATAC-seq) and chromatin immunoprecipitation sequencing we identified enrichment for the activator protein 1 (AP-1) transcription factor c-Jun at regions of early transient accessibility at fibroblast-specific enhancers. Expression of a dominant negative AP-1 mutant (dnAP-1) reduced accessibility and expression of fibroblast genes, overcoming the barrier to reprogramming. Remarkably, efficient reprogramming of human fibroblasts to induced pluripotent stem cells was achieved by transduction with vectors expressing SOX2, KLF4, and inducible dnAP-1, demonstrating that dnAP-1 can substitute for exogenous human OCT4. Mechanistically, we show that the AP-1 component c-Jun has two unexpected temporally distinct functions in human reprogramming: 1) to potentiate fibroblast enhancer accessibility and fibroblast-specific gene expression, and 2) to bind to and repress OCT4 as a complex with MBD3. Our findings highlight AP-1 as a previously unrecognized potent dual gatekeeper of the somatic cell state.&#34;},{&#34;apaCitation&#34;:&#34;Grapotte, M., Saraswat, M., Bessiere, C., Menichelli, C., Ramilowski, J. A., Severin, J., … Lecellieree, C.-H. (2021). Discovery of widespread transcription initiation at microsatellites predictable by sequence-based deep neural network. &lt;i>NATURE COMMUNICATIONS&lt;/i>, &lt;i>12&lt;/i>(1), 3297.&#34;,&#34;capCitation&#34;:&#34;&lt;span class=\&#34;title\&#34;>\n  &lt;span>Discovery of widespread transcription initiation at microsatellites predictable by sequence-based deep neural network&lt;/span>\n  &lt;i>NATURE COMMUNICATIONS&lt;/i>\n&lt;/span>\n&lt;span class=\&#34;authors\&#34;>Grapotte, M., Saraswat, M., Bessiere, C., Menichelli, C., Ramilowski, J. A., Severin, J., Hayashizaki, Y., Itoh, M., Tagami, M., Murata, M., Kojima-Ishiyamas, M., Noma, S., Noguchi, S., Kasukawa, T., Hasegawa, A., Suzuki, H., Nishiyori-Sueki, H., Frith, M. C., Chatelain, C., Carninci, P., de Hoom, M. J. L., Wasserman, W. W., Brehelin, L., Lecellieree, C., FANTOM Consortium&lt;/span>\n\n&lt;span class=\&#34;details\&#34;>\n   &lt;span class=\&#34;year\&#34;>2021&lt;/span>; &lt;span class=\&#34;volume\&#34;>12 (1)&lt;/span>&lt;span class=\&#34;pages\&#34;>: 3297&lt;/span>\n&lt;/span>&#34;,&#34;chicagoCitation&#34;:&#34;Grapotte, Mathys, Manu Saraswat, Chloe Bessiere, Christophe Menichelli, Jordan A. Ramilowski, et al. 2021. “Discovery of Widespread Transcription Initiation at Microsatellites Predictable by Sequence-Based Deep Neural Network.” &lt;i>NATURE COMMUNICATIONS&lt;/i> 12 (1). NATURE RESEARCH: 3297.&#34;,&#34;detail&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;&lt;h4>Abstract&lt;/h4>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;abstract\&#34;>Using the Cap Analysis of Gene Expression (CAGE) technology, the FANTOM5 consortium provided one of the most comprehensive maps of transcription start sites (TSSs) in several species. Strikingly, ~72% of them could not be assigned to a specific gene and initiate at unconventional regions, outside promoters or enhancers. Here, we probe these unassigned TSSs and show that, in all species studied, a significant fraction of CAGE peaks initiate at microsatellites, also called short tandem repeats (STRs). To confirm this transcription, we develop Cap Trap RNA-seq, a technology which combines cap trapping and long read MinION sequencing. We train sequence-based deep learning models able to predict CAGE signal at STRs with high accuracy. These models unveil the importance of STR surrounding sequences not only to distinguish STR classes, but also to predict the level of transcription initiation. Importantly, genetic variants linked to human diseases are preferentially found at STRs with high transcription initiation level, supporting the biological and clinical relevance of transcription initiation at STRs. Together, our results extend the repertoire of non-coding transcription associated with DNA tandem repeats and complexify STR polymorphism.&lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;doi\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://doi.org/10.1038/s41467-021-23143-7\&#34;>DOI 10.1038/s41467-021-23143-7&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;wos\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://ws.isiknowledge.com/cps/openurl/service?url_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;amp;rft_id=info:ut/000660869500001\&#34;>Web of Science ID 000660869500001&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;pub-med\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/34078885\&#34;>PubMedID 34078885&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;pub-med-central\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8172540\&#34;>PubMedCentralID PMC8172540&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Abstract:\nUsing the Cap Analysis of Gene Expression (CAGE) technology, the FANTOM5 consortium provided one of the most comprehensive maps of transcription start sites (TSSs) in several species. Strikingly, ~72% of them could not be assigned to a specific gene and initiate at unconventional regions, outside promoters or enhancers. Here, we probe these unassigned TSSs and show that, in all species studied, a significant fraction of CAGE peaks initiate at microsatellites, also called short tandem repeats (STRs). To confirm this transcription, we develop Cap Trap RNA-seq, a technology which combines cap trapping and long read MinION sequencing. We train sequence-based deep learning models able to predict CAGE signal at STRs with high accuracy. These models unveil the importance of STR surrounding sequences not only to distinguish STR classes, but also to predict the level of transcription initiation. Importantly, genetic variants linked to human diseases are preferentially found at STRs with high transcription initiation level, supporting the biological and clinical relevance of transcription initiation at STRs. Together, our results extend the repertoire of non-coding transcription associated with DNA tandem repeats and complexify STR polymorphism.\nDOI: 10.1038/s41467-021-23143-7, https://doi.org/10.1038/s41467-021-23143-7\nWeb of Science ID: 000660869500001, https://ws.isiknowledge.com/cps/openurl/service?url_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_id=info:ut/000660869500001\nPubMedID: 34078885, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/34078885\nPubMedCentralID: PMC8172540, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8172540&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:null},&#34;doiId&#34;:&#34;10.1038/s41467-021-23143-7&#34;,&#34;doiUrl&#34;:&#34;https://doi.org/10.1038/s41467-021-23143-7&#34;,&#34;featured&#34;:false,&#34;firstPublished&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;Jun 2, 2021 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Jun 2, 2021 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:&#34;2021-06-02T00:00:00.000-07:00&#34;},&#34;mlaCitation&#34;:&#34;Grapotte, Mathys et al. “Discovery of Widespread Transcription Initiation at Microsatellites Predictable by Sequence-Based Deep Neural Network.” &lt;i>NATURE COMMUNICATIONS&lt;/i> 12.1 (2021): 3297. Print.&#34;,&#34;pubMedId&#34;:&#34;34078885&#34;,&#34;pubMedUrl&#34;:&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/34078885&#34;,&#34;publicationId&#34;:&#34;847500&#34;,&#34;title&#34;:&#34;Discovery of widespread transcription initiation at microsatellites predictable by sequence-based deep neural network&#34;,&#34;type&#34;:&#34;article&#34;,&#34;contentClass&#34;:&#34;publication article&#34;,&#34;abstract&#34;:&#34;Using the Cap Analysis of Gene Expression (CAGE) technology, the FANTOM5 consortium provided one of the most comprehensive maps of transcription start sites (TSSs) in several species. Strikingly, ~72% of them could not be assigned to a specific gene and initiate at unconventional regions, outside promoters or enhancers. Here, we probe these unassigned TSSs and show that, in all species studied, a significant fraction of CAGE peaks initiate at microsatellites, also called short tandem repeats (STRs). To confirm this transcription, we develop Cap Trap RNA-seq, a technology which combines cap trapping and long read MinION sequencing. We train sequence-based deep learning models able to predict CAGE signal at STRs with high accuracy. These models unveil the importance of STR surrounding sequences not only to distinguish STR classes, but also to predict the level of transcription initiation. Importantly, genetic variants linked to human diseases are preferentially found at STRs with high transcription initiation level, supporting the biological and clinical relevance of transcription initiation at STRs. Together, our results extend the repertoire of non-coding transcription associated with DNA tandem repeats and complexify STR polymorphism.&#34;},{&#34;apaCitation&#34;:&#34;Marinov, G. K., Trevino, A. E., Xiang, T., Kundaje, A., Grossman, A. R., &amp;amp; Greenleaf, W. J. (2021). Transcription-dependent domain-scale three-dimensional genome organization in the dinoflagellate Breviolum minutum. &lt;i>Nature Genetics&lt;/i>.&#34;,&#34;capCitation&#34;:&#34;&lt;span class=\&#34;title\&#34;>\n  &lt;span>Transcription-dependent domain-scale three-dimensional genome organization in the dinoflagellate Breviolum minutum.&lt;/span>\n  &lt;i>Nature genetics&lt;/i>\n&lt;/span>\n&lt;span class=\&#34;authors\&#34;>Marinov, G. K., Trevino, A. E., Xiang, T., Kundaje, A., Grossman, A. R., Greenleaf, W. J.&lt;/span>\n\n&lt;span class=\&#34;details\&#34;>\n   &lt;span class=\&#34;year\&#34;>2021&lt;/span>\n&lt;/span>&#34;,&#34;chicagoCitation&#34;:&#34;Marinov, Georgi K., Alexandro E. Trevino, Tingting Xiang, Anshul Kundaje, Arthur R. Grossman, et al. 2021. “Transcription-Dependent Domain-Scale Three-Dimensional Genome Organization in the Dinoflagellate Breviolum Minutum.” &lt;i>Nature Genetics&lt;/i>.&#34;,&#34;detail&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;&lt;h4>Abstract&lt;/h4>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;abstract\&#34;>Dinoflagellate chromosomes represent a unique evolutionary experiment, as they exist in a permanently condensed, liquid crystalline state; are not packaged by histones; and contain genes organized into tandem gene arrays, with minimal transcriptional regulation. We analyze the three-dimensional genome of Breviolum minutum, and find large topological domains (dinoflagellate topologically associating domains, which we term &#39;dinoTADs&#39;) without chromatin loops, which are demarcated by convergent gene array boundaries. Transcriptional inhibition disrupts dinoTADs, implicating transcription-induced supercoiling as the primary topological force in dinoflagellates.&lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;doi\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://doi.org/10.1038/s41588-021-00848-5\&#34;>DOI 10.1038/s41588-021-00848-5&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;pub-med\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/33927397\&#34;>PubMedID 33927397&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Abstract:\nDinoflagellate chromosomes represent a unique evolutionary experiment, as they exist in a permanently condensed, liquid crystalline state; are not packaged by histones; and contain genes organized into tandem gene arrays, with minimal transcriptional regulation. We analyze the three-dimensional genome of Breviolum minutum, and find large topological domains (dinoflagellate topologically associating domains, which we term &#39;dinoTADs&#39;) without chromatin loops, which are demarcated by convergent gene array boundaries. Transcriptional inhibition disrupts dinoTADs, implicating transcription-induced supercoiling as the primary topological force in dinoflagellates.\nDOI: 10.1038/s41588-021-00848-5, https://doi.org/10.1038/s41588-021-00848-5\n\nPubMedID: 33927397, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/33927397&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:null},&#34;doiId&#34;:&#34;10.1038/s41588-021-00848-5&#34;,&#34;doiUrl&#34;:&#34;https://doi.org/10.1038/s41588-021-00848-5&#34;,&#34;featured&#34;:false,&#34;firstPublished&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;Apr 29, 2021 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Apr 29, 2021 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:&#34;2021-04-29T00:00:00.000-07:00&#34;},&#34;mlaCitation&#34;:&#34;Marinov, Georgi K. et al. “Transcription-Dependent Domain-Scale Three-Dimensional Genome Organization in the Dinoflagellate Breviolum Minutum.” &lt;i>Nature genetics&lt;/i> (2021): n. pag. Print.&#34;,&#34;pubMedId&#34;:&#34;33927397&#34;,&#34;pubMedUrl&#34;:&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/33927397&#34;,&#34;publicationId&#34;:&#34;811226&#34;,&#34;title&#34;:&#34;Transcription-dependent domain-scale three-dimensional genome organization in the dinoflagellate Breviolum minutum.&#34;,&#34;type&#34;:&#34;article&#34;,&#34;contentClass&#34;:&#34;publication article&#34;,&#34;abstract&#34;:&#34;Dinoflagellate chromosomes represent a unique evolutionary experiment, as they exist in a permanently condensed, liquid crystalline state; are not packaged by histones; and contain genes organized into tandem gene arrays, with minimal transcriptional regulation. We analyze the three-dimensional genome of Breviolum minutum, and find large topological domains (dinoflagellate topologically associating domains, which we term &#39;dinoTADs&#39;) without chromatin loops, which are demarcated by convergent gene array boundaries. Transcriptional inhibition disrupts dinoTADs, implicating transcription-induced supercoiling as the primary topological force in dinoflagellates.&#34;},{&#34;apaCitation&#34;:&#34;Cheng, J., Celik, M. H., Kundaje, A., &amp;amp; Gagneur, J. (2021). 