nscription, DNase I hypersensitivity, transcription factor binding, chromatin modifications and replication domains throughout the mouse genome in diverse cell and tissue types. By comparing with the human genome, we not only confirm substantial conservation in the newly annotated potential functional sequences, but also find a large degree of divergence of sequences involved in transcriptional regulation, chromatin state and higher order chromatin organization. Our results illuminate the wide range of evolutionary forces acting on genes and their regulatory regions, and provide a general resource for research into mammalian biology and mechanisms of human diseases.\nDOI: 10.1038/nature13992, https://dx.doi.org/10.1038/nature13992\n\nPubMedID: 25409824, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25409824&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:null},&#34;doiId&#34;:&#34;10.1038/nature13992&#34;,&#34;doiUrl&#34;:&#34;https://dx.doi.org/10.1038/nature13992&#34;,&#34;featured&#34;:false,&#34;firstPublished&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;Nov 20, 2014 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Nov 20, 2014 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:&#34;2014-11-20T00:00:00.000-08:00&#34;},&#34;mlaCitation&#34;:&#34;Yue, Feng et al. “A Comparative Encyclopedia of DNA Elements in the Mouse Genome.” &lt;i>Nature&lt;/i> 515.7527 (2014): 355–64. Print.&#34;,&#34;pubMedId&#34;:&#34;25409824&#34;,&#34;pubMedUrl&#34;:&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25409824&#34;,&#34;publicationId&#34;:&#34;393417&#34;,&#34;title&#34;:&#34;A comparative encyclopedia of DNA elements in the mouse genome.&#34;,&#34;type&#34;:&#34;article&#34;,&#34;contentClass&#34;:&#34;publication article&#34;,&#34;abstract&#34;:&#34;The laboratory mouse shares the majority of its protein-coding genes with humans, making it the premier model organism in biomedical research, yet the two mammals differ in significant ways. To gain greater insights into both shared and species-specific transcriptional and cellular regulatory programs in the mouse, the Mouse ENCODE Consortium has mapped transcription, DNase I hypersensitivity, transcription factor binding, chromatin modifications and replication domains throughout the mouse genome in diverse cell and tissue types. By comparing with the human genome, we not only confirm substantial conservation in the newly annotated potential functional sequences, but also find a large degree of divergence of sequences involved in transcriptional regulation, chromatin state and higher order chromatin organization. Our results illuminate the wide range of evolutionary forces acting on genes and their regulatory regions, and provide a general resource for research into mammalian biology and mechanisms of human diseases.&#34;},{&#34;apaCitation&#34;:&#34;Cheng, Y., Ma, Z., Kim, B.-H. H., Wu, W., Cayting, P., Boyle, A. P., … Snyder, M. P. (2014). Principles of regulatory information conservation between mouse and human. &lt;i>Nature&lt;/i>, &lt;i>515&lt;/i>(7527), 371–5.&#34;,&#34;capCitation&#34;:&#34;&lt;span class=\&#34;title\&#34;>\n  &lt;span>Principles of regulatory information conservation between mouse and human.&lt;/span>\n  &lt;i>Nature&lt;/i>\n&lt;/span>\n&lt;span class=\&#34;authors\&#34;>Cheng, Y., Ma, Z., Kim, B. H., Wu, W., Cayting, P., Boyle, A. P., Sundaram, V., Xing, X., Dogan, N., Li, J., Euskirchen, G., Lin, S., Lin, Y., Visel, A., Kawli, T., Yang, X., Patacsil, D., Keller, C. A., Giardine, B., Kundaje, A., Wang, T., Pennacchio, L. A., Weng, Z., Hardison, R. C., Snyder, M. P.&lt;/span>\n\n&lt;span class=\&#34;details\&#34;>\n   &lt;span class=\&#34;year\&#34;>2014&lt;/span>; &lt;span class=\&#34;volume\&#34;>515 (7527)&lt;/span>&lt;span class=\&#34;pages\&#34;>: 371-5&lt;/span>\n&lt;/span>&#34;,&#34;chicagoCitation&#34;:&#34;Cheng, Yong, Zhihai Ma, Bong-Hyun H. Kim, Weisheng Wu, Philip Cayting, et al. 2014. “Principles of Regulatory Information Conservation between Mouse and Human.” &lt;i>Nature&lt;/i> 515 (7527): 371–75.&#34;,&#34;detail&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;&lt;h4>Abstract&lt;/h4>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;abstract\&#34;>To broaden our understanding of the evolution of gene regulation mechanisms, we generated occupancy profiles for 34 orthologous transcription factors (TFs) in human-mouse erythroid progenitor, lymphoblast and embryonic stem-cell lines. By combining the genome-wide transcription factor occupancy repertoires, associated epigenetic signals, and co-association patterns, here we deduce several evolutionary principles of gene regulatory features operating since the mouse and human lineages diverged. The genomic distribution profiles, primary binding motifs, chromatin states, and DNA methylation preferences are well conserved for TF-occupied sequences. However, the extent to which orthologous DNA segments are bound by orthologous TFs varies both among TFs and with genomic location: binding at promoters is more highly conserved than binding at distal elements. Notably, occupancy-conserved TF-occupied sequences tend to be pleiotropic; they function in several tissues and also co-associate with many TFs. Single nucleotide variants at sites with potential regulatory functions are enriched in occupancy-conserved TF-occupied sequences.&lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;doi\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://doi.org/10.1038/nature13985\&#34;>DOI 10.1038/nature13985&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;pub-med\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25409826\&#34;>PubMedID 25409826&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>\n  &lt;p class=\&#34;pub-med-central\&#34;>\n    &lt;span>View details for &lt;a href=\&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4343047\&#34;>PubMedCentralID PMC4343047&lt;/a>&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/p>&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Abstract:\nTo broaden our understanding of the evolution of gene regulation mechanisms, we generated occupancy profiles for 34 orthologous transcription factors (TFs) in human-mouse erythroid progenitor, lymphoblast and embryonic stem-cell lines. By combining the genome-wide transcription factor occupancy repertoires, associated epigenetic signals, and co-association patterns, here we deduce several evolutionary principles of gene regulatory features operating since the mouse and human lineages diverged. The genomic distribution profiles, primary binding motifs, chromatin states, and DNA methylation preferences are well conserved for TF-occupied sequences. However, the extent to which orthologous DNA segments are bound by orthologous TFs varies both among TFs and with genomic location: binding at promoters is more highly conserved than binding at distal elements. Notably, occupancy-conserved TF-occupied sequences tend to be pleiotropic; they function in several tissues and also co-associate with many TFs. Single nucleotide variants at sites with potential regulatory functions are enriched in occupancy-conserved TF-occupied sequences.\nDOI: 10.1038/nature13985, https://doi.org/10.1038/nature13985\n\nPubMedID: 25409826, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25409826\nPubMedCentralID: PMC4343047, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4343047&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:null},&#34;doiId&#34;:&#34;10.1038/nature13985&#34;,&#34;doiUrl&#34;:&#34;https://doi.org/10.1038/nature13985&#34;,&#34;featured&#34;:false,&#34;firstPublished&#34;:{&#34;html&#34;:&#34;Nov 20, 2014 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;text&#34;:&#34;Nov 20, 2014 00:00:00 AM&#34;,&#34;value&#34;:&#34;2014-11-20T00:00:00.000-08:00&#34;},&#34;mlaCitation&#34;:&#34;Cheng, Yong et al. “Principles of Regulatory Information Conservation between Mouse and Human.” &lt;i>Nature&lt;/i> 515.7527 (2014): 371–5. Print.&#34;,&#34;pubMedId&#34;:&#34;25409826&#34;,&#34;pubMedUrl&#34;:&#34;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25409826&#34;,&#34;publicationId&#34;:&#34;512471&#34;,&#34;title&#34;:&#34;Principles of regulatory information conservation between mouse and human.&#34;,&#34;type&#34;:&#34;article&#34;,&#34;contentClass&#34;:&#34;pub